{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ed0c6e76-f6eb-46eb-b3f2-c4527379cf05","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify details\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch?**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor throwing instead of `CreateUser`).\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pinpoints the exact call and lets you inspect the exception.\n\nFor **async** methods, use `Assert.ThrowsExceptionAsync<T>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1c8d8c17-09e8-4408-ab4e-99bcf731ef41","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no codebase exploration needed.","outputTokens":261,"requestId":"67D5:2636C7:2D256AC:31BD80F:69FD3E22"},"id":"1c8f8146-ba76-418d-95c0-0c7f369b7896","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:36:44.907Z","parentId":"04f29599-c56c-440c-b515-ade461a45e0d"}
